ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 5
 presents the coordination degree of various Indian States/UTs, classified from ‘primary development’ to ‘quality development’ level. In 2011, the coordination degree of various Indian States/UTs varied from ‘primary development’ to ‘good development’ (Fig. 5(a)). Fig. 5(a) also revealed that around 60 % of the States/UTs had ‘good development’ coordination in 2011. Himachal Pradesh has the highest coordination degree at 0.86, showing good coordination development (Fig. 6
). This high value is due to the higher interconnection between SDGs 6, 7 and 2 (WEF security), policy implementation, and stakeholder participation. In contrast, Lakshadweep has the lowest coordination degree at 0.67, reflecting a ‘primary development’ coordination stage, which suggests that in terms of the water-energy-food nexus, Lakshadweep faced challenges in coordinating and managing these resources effectively, possibly due to limited infrastructure and development in these areas. Besides Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh, Jharkhand, Bihar, Manipur, Meghalaya, Mizoram, Kerala, Karnataka and Andaman and Nicobar have an ‘intermediate development’ coordination degree, which implies that they were making progress in coordinating and managing water, energy, and food resources, but they still faced developmental challenges in these areas.
